Oh, where'd
you hear that?

200
00:07:29,149 --> 00:07:30,549
From my coach.

201
00:07:30,551 --> 00:07:31,983
And I heard it
from my coach,

202
00:07:31,985 --> 00:07:34,486
and he heard it from
his coach, and so on.

203
00:07:34,488 --> 00:07:36,154
Well, you didn't
hear it from science,

204
00:07:36,156 --> 00:07:38,089
'cause science says
that ain't true.

205
00:07:38,091 --> 00:07:40,258
Well, how much water
am I supposed to drink?

206
00:07:40,260 --> 00:07:42,394
Well, you can just drink
when you're thirsty.

207
00:07:42,396 --> 00:07:44,463
That's crazy,
you're a crazy person.

208
00:07:44,465 --> 00:07:45,664
Who are you?

209
00:07:45,666 --> 00:07:48,033
Oh, Patty, this is
Tamara Hew-Butler.

210
00:07:48,035 --> 00:07:50,969
She's a professor of exercise
science at Oakland University.

211
00:07:50,971 --> 00:07:52,771
Our bodies already possess

212
00:07:52,773 --> 00:07:55,073
an extremely sensitive
measure of dehydration.

213
00:07:55,075 --> 00:07:56,141
It's called thirst.

214
00:07:56,143 --> 00:07:58,643
As long as we drink
when we feel thirsty,

215
00:07:58,645 --> 00:07:59,911
we really
won't dehydrate.

216
00:07:59,913 --> 00:08:02,681
That's how humans have done it
for millions of years,

217
00:08:02,683 --> 00:08:03,882
and it's worked out fine.

218
00:08:03,884 --> 00:08:06,218
The fact is, truly dangerous
levels of dehydration

219
00:08:06,220 --> 00:08:08,720
are incredibly rare
and only occur in cases

220
00:08:08,722 --> 00:08:11,022
of extreme sickness
or isolation.

221
00:08:11,024 --> 00:08:12,791
As long as you have
free access to water

222
00:08:12,793 --> 00:08:14,526
and you drink
when you're thirsty,

223
00:08:14,528 --> 00:08:16,161
you'll be fine.

224
00:08:16,163 --> 00:08:18,763
